
# alt+shift+r to refresh



# ● Research Summary: Web Search TUI Tool Integration
#
#   Yes, absolutely! You can create a web search TUI tool and integrate it with both tmux and i3. Here's what I
#   found:
#
#   Existing TUI Web Search Tools
#
#   1. googler (Google search)
#   - Full TUI with interactive "omniprompt"
#   - Navigate results with n/p, open in browser, fire new searches without exiting
#   - Clean, fast, no ads
#   - Python-based, requires Python 3.6+
#   - Install: sudo apt install googler or from GitHub
#
#   2. ddgr (DuckDuckGo search)
#   - Similar to googler but privacy-focused
#   - Works over Tor network
#   - Supports DuckDuckGo Bangs
#   - Interactive TUI interface
#
#   3. Other options:
#   - chawan - Full TUI web browser with CSS/JS support
#   - ggl - CLI tool for Google/YouTube/Gmail/Wiki/GitHub searches
#
#   Integration Approaches
#
#   For tmux (what you're using):
#
#   # Add to ~/.config/tmux/tmux.conf
#   bind-key g display-popup -E -w 90% -h 90% "googler --colors bjdxxy"
#   bind-key G display-popup -E -w 90% -h 90% "ddgr"
#
#   - Uses display-popup (like you have for tms)
#   - Opens in floating popup window
#   - -E closes popup when command exits
#   - Adjust width/height as needed
#
#   For i3 (alternative):
#
#   # Add to ~/.config/i3/config
#   bindsym $mod+g exec --no-startup-id i3-sensible-terminal -e googler
#   bindsym $mod+Shift+g exec --no-startup-id "alacritty --class floating -e googler"
#
#   # Make it float
#   for_window [class="floating"] floating enable
#
#   Or use rofi for input then pass to googler:
#   bindsym $mod+g exec --no-startup-id "i3-sensible-terminal -e googler $(rofi -dmenu -p 'Search:')"
#
#   Quick Setup (Recommended)
#
#   1. Install googler:
#   sudo apt install googler  # Debian/Ubuntu
#   # or
#   pip install googler
#   2. Add tmux binding:
#   bind-key g display-popup -E -w 90% -h 90% "googler"
#   3. Use it: Ctrl-w + g → type search → navigate results
#
#   Why This Works
#
#   - Both googler/ddgr are designed as TUI apps with omniprompt mode
#   - tmux's display-popup creates floating windows (like your tms setup)
#   - i3 can launch terminal windows with keybindings easily
#   - No custom plugin needed - just keybinding + external command
#
#   Want me to install googler/ddgr and set up the tmux binding for you?

set $mod Mod1 
floating_modifier $mod
# mod+left click to re-position tiled window
# mod+left click to move floating window
# mod+right click to resize floating window

# Start XDG autostart .desktop files using dex. See also
# https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/XDG_Autostart
exec --no-startup-id dex --autostart --environment i3

# xss-lock grabs a logind suspend inhibit lock and will use i3lock to lock the
# screen before suspend. Use loginctl lock-session to lock your screen.
exec --no-startup-id xss-lock --transfer-sleep-lock -- i3lock --nofork

# NetworkManager is the most popular way to manage wireless networks on Linux,
# and nm-applet is a desktop environment-independent system tray GUI for it.
exec --no-startup-id nm-applet

# Use pactl to adjust volume in PulseAudio.
set $refresh_i3status killall -SIGUSR1 i3status
bindsym XF86AudioRaiseVolume exec --no-startup-id pactl set-sink-volume @DEFAULT_SINK@ +5% && $refresh_i3status
bindsym XF86AudioLowerVolume exec --no-startup-id pactl set-sink-volume @DEFAULT_SINK@ -5% && $refresh_i3status
bindsym XF86AudioMute exec --no-startup-id pactl set-sink-mute @DEFAULT_SINK@ toggle && $refresh_i3status
bindsym XF86AudioMicMute exec --no-startup-id pactl set-source-mute @DEFAULT_SOURCE@ toggle && $refresh_i3status

